Here is a way to look at this. Is the client required to understand  
that it needs to pass &quot;/view&quot; in the URI to &quot;view&quot; this document, and,  
perhaps, add &quot;/edit&quot; in the URI to &quot;edit&quot; this document? If so, that  
is not RESTful as it violates the uniform interface. If, on the  
otherhand, the server is providing URIs for these actions within the  
hypermedia, that will then drive the client to use GET and POST/PUT to  
do these actions, then it may not be violating the uniform interface.

To be more specific, the HTML might contain a link to &quot;/edit? 
docid=...&quot;, a GET to which would render a HTML page with a form, and  
form submission would do a POST to &quot;/edit?docid=...&quot;. Some may argue  
that this is incorrect (since the URIs to get and edit the resource  
are not the same), but that is where we are with HTML.

Subbu

